Test it.
Testing, testing, Friday the fourth.
Testing, okay, testing.
This is Friday, October 5th.
We're in the MSC, and I have the honor of
recording the memories of his A&M experiences with Mr. Michele Halbuty, class of 1930.
To introduce yourself, Mr. Halbuty, to anyone that might hear this tape or read a transcription, describe your family background growing up.
When did mom and dad come to this country?
Where did you all live?
Where'd you go to high school?
I went to high school in Beaumont, Texas.
I was born in Beaumont, Texas on the 21st of June, 1909.
In nine months, I'll be 73 years old.
My parents came to the United States separately.
They didn't know each other until they met each other in Beaumont, Texas.
Were they both Lebanese?
Both Lebanese.
They were born in Lebanon.
I had five, I had six children, five boys and one girl.
There's only two of us left.
Two boys and one girl left.
I came to... What did your dad do for a living?
We were very poor, extremely poor.
He built a little grocery store.
He was making a few dollars a day to keep the family alive.
Were you all down in South Park or in Beaumont?
No, we were in Beaumont.
Did you go to Beaumont High?
You were Royal Purple?
I went to Beaumont High, but we didn't have any middle school.
We went from the lower grades into high school directly.
What led you to dream of going to college?
Well... Did someone encourage it?
Did you think of it?
No.
Of course I thought about it, but I thought about it because of a reason.
And when I was a freshman in high school, a teacher got up and started talking something about the universe.
And it triggered something in my mind that the Earth was more than 5,000 years old, which my Sunday school teacher was telling the class.
So I went up to her and I said, Miss Emma, how old is the earth?
She said, I can't tell you, Michelle.
You're going to have to go to the library and find out for yourself.
I said, why can't you tell me?
She said, I won't tell you.
You're going to have to go find out yourself.
I said, how?
She said, look in the books of geology.
So I looked in the books in Georgia, and I got so interested in Georgia, I read all the books.
And I found out the Earth at that time was estimated to be 3.5 billion years old, which is now 5.5.
It took a while for me to understand why she didn't tell me.
And then I realized that the Stokes trial was coming up.
And she didn't want to have anything to do with evolution or anything to do with fundamentalism or anything to do with creationism.
And she just didn't want to tell me because she was afraid she'd lose her job.
And I understand that pretty well.
And this is the reason why I became a geologist, because I wanted to be a geologist.
I didn't have petroleum in mind.
I loved the science.
I still do.
Did you have some other important teachers in high school important to you?
No, I'm not going to get into that because I don't remember.
What led you to come to Texas A&M?
Why here instead of somewhere else?
I didn't want to come to Texas A&M at first.
I wanted to go to Oklahoma.
I found out that Oklahoma had a great geological school, and I found out that that's where I wanted to go.
But I had saved my money selling newspapers, working at odd jobs, and I had just enough money to register, and I figured that that's enough.
And when I checked the portfolios and everything else, I found out that because I live in Texas, I'd have to pay more money to go to Oklahoma, and I said, I don't have it.
So I started checking on Texas A&M, and I had just enough money to register at Texas A&M.
So I decided I'd come here, because I checked and found out that they were going to establish a new science department.
And I figured that I could be involved in the beginning of the science.
How did you get over to A&M?
Did you come on the train or the bus?
Train.
Came on the train.
I landed over here at that old depot.
I understand they're going to reinstate it or something.
What did you bring with you?
What kind of gear?
What kind of stuff?
I just have a small, small suitcase bag and I walked toward the administration building and went into the register and I found out I was $50 short.
And so I was determined I wasn't going to go back home because I knew that if I did, I'd never see another campus in my life.
that I would have to work to try to support the family.
And so I inquired about who would be of help.
And I heard some students say that Prexy Walton ran the institution.
Prexy Walton did this and Prexy Walton did that.
I said, well, that man must be big enough to loan me $50.
So I knocked on the door and Mr. Williamson, who was his secretary, talked to me and wanted to know what was going on, and I told him.
In the meantime, Walton stepped out from his office
And she held him up.
She was doing this.
I didn't know what she was doing that for.
So he stood at the door and listened to my tale.
And I told him, I said, if it will owe me $50, I'll pay him back if it takes the last shirt off my back.
So he said, come on in, young man.
I walked in.
He asked me something about me, something about my family.
And he said, you came short.
I said, no, I saw in the brochure that I had enough money.
He said, well, there's some things that you have.
He said, we support you, and we do a lot of things for you.
And so therefore, you have to have $50 more.
And I said, well, will you loan me that $50?
We talked a while, and he said, all right.
So he gave me two 20s and a 10, and I registered.
Then I worked for 25 cents an hour during that whole year to pay him back, and I did.
What were your jobs?
My main job was rowing and cutting grass in front of the administration building from one end to the other.
And then I solicited small jobs from people for cutting their yard and cutting their roses and fixing their lawns.
Anything where I could make 25 cents, I worked.
And I had my grades, took care of them, and I just kept working to get that 25 cents.
What dormitory were you assigned as a freshman?
We were in the shacks.
And where were they?
Describe the shacks, please.
I don't know exactly what location, where they were, but it's the shacks.
You ought to know something about the shacks.
If you've taken interviews, has anyone that you've taken an interview with said that they were living in the shacks?
Mrs.
Rudder has told me a little bit about what Mr.
Rudder remembered.
I don't know whether he was young enough to be in the shacks.
The shacks were 1926, 1927.
Oh, is that all?
That's all.
Why were they built?
They were built to take care of people that were coming into the university.
I mean, they had more students than they could accommodate in the dorms.
I don't know whether they did or not.
I have no idea.
All I know is that we lived in the shacks.
How many were in your shack?
I think there were four.
Four.
And bunk beds?
Bunk beds.
Did you have running water?
Oh yes, we had, well no, there was a common area, common area where you had, where you had latrines and water and even showers.
There was nothing in the room, nothing in the shack that you could be able to wash your hands or brush your teeth or anything.
And who were your roommates?
I don't know and I don't want to talk about it.
Describe a typical day.
What time did you get up and what did you do when?
I got up enough to go to classes and when I got back I sat down and studied.
Did you study in the shack or in the library?
No, in the shack.
In the shack?
Did you and your buddies ever play any jokes or do any... Oh, there were a lot of them, I guess, going on in that area, like there was in any other area.
But hazing was very prevalent.
Describe that, please.
They beat the hell out of you.
That's what they did.
Sophomores, some of you ran into sophomores that were all right.
Then you ran into some sophomores that wanted to take it out on you for no reason whatsoever.
And I had one, all he wanted to do was beat me.
And he did.
And he did.
And bent over, freshman.
So I went home that Christmas.
My mother came to the bed to pull the cover on me, and she saw blood.
And when she did, she fainted over me and wanted to know why I was so bruised, bleeding.
That's how bad it was.
Now did they use boards or were they...
Boards.
They used boards about that wide.
And they used anything.
Some of them used coat hangers.
This particular sophomore
He just gave me a lot of trouble.
He said, get a freshman, go steal me some eggs.
And I had to run over to the farm and get eggs and bring them in, things of that kind.
What would he do with the eggs?
Did he eat them?
I don't know what he did with them, but he harassed me to no end.
And he said, I don't like anybody from Beaumont.
I don't like anybody from Beaumont, Tyson.
So I just took it because I wanted to stay.
And so I worked at the Spieser as a waiter.
And the last day that we were going to have lunch in Spieser, I was carrying this tray of milk, coffee,
And I think it was honey and other things.
And I was just carrying it to the table.
And I saw this guy.
And I guess the devil got a hold of me.
He said, dump it all over him.
And I did.
And he got up.
He said, I'll kill you, freshman.
I said, no, you won't.
Not anymore.
You bastard.
Sit down.
And then I decided I'm going to do everything I can to eliminate hazing in this institution.
And when I was a sophomore, I really worked.
I went to the officials at this university.
I went even to members of the Board of Regents.
I told them that we ought to stop this thing.
And finally they did.
They did it the year that I was there.
That's good.
Describe President Walton as a human.
President Walton was a wonderful man.
He was very compassionate.
Otherwise, he wouldn't have loaned me that $50.
He took a chance on me for $50 to him.
Might have been something that he didn't want to get rid of, but he loaned it to me because of the way I talked to him.
I told him, I said, you don't have to worry about that $50.
It'll be paid.
And it was.
He was big man?
What size?
He was, yes, he was about I would say 6'2", if I remember correctly.
He was kind of half bald in a way.
Very delightful man.
And his secretary was so good.
Now his office was in the academic building?
In the old administration building.
In the old administration building.
You know where that is?
The one with the dome?
Yeah.
Yeah.
Yeah.
Now that's called the academic building.
I didn't know.
I just called it the administration building from the time I got here.
Did students attempt to play any tricks on the Waltons at their house?
Not that I know of.
Not that I know of.
Were you majoring in geology your first year?
They didn't have geology per se.
They had science.
Yes, sir.
And then I particularly majored myself.
I just went to the main libraries and took all the books I could on geology.
And then the professor that was teaching me the science knew that I was interested in geology and he helped me.
Who was that?
Do you remember?
I don't remember his name.
I think his name was Bert.
But anyway, Dr. Lonsdale came in when I was a junior, and he added the department.
He created the Department of Geology.
And then I decided that I was going to just be a scientist, and I wanted to study geology.
All right, that first year,
You got your job pretty quickly.
You worked mowing the grass and also at Sabisa your first year.
Had both those jobs.
What, Sabisa?
You worked at Sabisa.
Oh, I worked at Sabisa.
I worked at a restaurant called the Greasy Spoon.
Yes, oh.
And I worked there for 25 cents an hour.
I was a waiter.
I worked in a grocery store, helping the man serve the people in that area.
I worked in every way possible.
And earning 25 cents was arduous.
And they had a confectionery in the old YMCA building.
And I'd go in there, and I'd see these people ordering thick malts.
And they'd put one ice cream and malt, ice cream and malt.
And I'd sit there, and I'd look at it.
I'd say, gee, I guess one of these things, I got to buy one.
It cost $0.25.
And finally I saved 25 cents, and I said, now I'm going to go get my thick bolt.
I went to that, and I said, what do you want, freshman?
Give me a sarsaparilla for a nickel.
I just couldn't spend 25 cents knowing how hard I was working.
Now, you went to class.
In the afternoons, you worked.
I worked whenever I could.
I worked sometime at night.
The upperclassmen asked me to do something, go to the library, get them a book, something like that.
He'd give me 10 cents, 20 cents, 25 cents.
I just kept every nickel I could possibly make.
About what time?
I ran into old books at the end of the half semester.
There were books and I'd pick them up and I'd sell them.
The library then, was Tommy Mayo the librarian still?
I don't know.
Professor of English?
I don't know.
Was the library a pleasant place then?
Yes.
Now what other kinds of hazing was there in addition to the paddling?
What else did a freshman have to do?
Abusive, abusive, harassment.
And there were some sophomores that were, I think, a little bit vengeful for every reason whatsoever.
And they would get mad at themselves and take it out on the freshmen.
I've seen them whip freshmen that did nothing except they just wanted to get somebody to whip.
It was a bad, bad two years.
Bad, bad.
Do you remember going, as a freshman, going to the football games?
Oh, yes.
Describe that.
I was working for a family between here and Bryan.
I was taking care of the yard, and I'd go in there and work for the last hour, four or five, from four to five, or five to six, or even from six to seven if I could.
I'd work two hours, and she'd give me 50 cents.
And then one Saturday, I went over there early, and she saw me outside.
She said, what are you doing outside?
I said, show.
I said, well, I'm going to work four hours with you.
I need that dollar.
She said, I'm not going to pay you today.
You get back and go to see that football game.
She said, that's part of your education.
I said, I don't want you to be just working all the time.
I said, well, I have to.
She said, no, just you go.
So I went and I realized what she was telling me, that I have other things to do besides working.
And I did.
Did you all march into the game the way the Corps does now?
No, I don't think we marched in.
We marched to speeds of uh-oh, things like that, but I don't remember marching into the game.
Did you stand up at the games?
Oh yes.
We did that regardless of that.
Regardless of that 12th band and anything else, we did that because we wanted to.
What kinds of things did the students do during the games?
Same thing they're doing now.
Did anybody do any drinking during the game?
No, I don't think so.
There might have been one or two, you know, but it was never shown.
It was never demonstrated in any way.
Were there many dates?
Did the Aggies have dates?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, they went to Navasota, Hearn, any place where they can get dates.
And a lot of girls came down for special occasions from Ditton, which was that time.
It was then CIA.
Yeah.
And Brian supplied a lot of girls.
And we got along all right.
Being in the military school, it was the greatest thing that ever happened to me because we were so poor.
I couldn't buy clothes, and when you passed the physical examination and were accepted as a student, they gave you two sets of uniforms, and that was clothes that I couldn't have bought.
And I loved the Corps.
I really loved the Corps.
What did you like best about the Corps?
Well, I was learning something about the military and also about the history of the United States, the wars that have been fought and the wars that have been fought elsewhere.
So it was an exhilarating experience just to be a member of the Corps and be at A&M.
I don't think we had, when I was a freshman, I don't think we had 1,800, 1,900 students.
When I graduated, I think there were just a little over 2,000.
Almost all of them lived on campus?
All of them on campus, all in the cadet corps, except there was one house, one dormitory, in which there were 40 students who couldn't pass the examination for some handicap or something like that.
And they would accept them, put them in this dormitory, and we referred to them as casuals.
So they didn't wear a uniform?
No, no, no.
But they were all boys?
Oh, yeah, absolutely.
Were there any, in the early 20s, there were two or three faculty daughters allowed to attend classes.
Were there any girls attending any classes when you were here?
I don't remember.
Well, I bet you would if there were girls.
I don't remember.
Dr. Ball had a beautiful daughter.
And Dr. Ball, he was a science teacher, a biology teacher, I think.
Funny, I can remember him.
And we became very good friends.
And it could be possible that his daughter attended some classes.
Now, were there faculty members already living on the campus in the houses over here?
Sure, yes, yes.
That's where most of them lived.
That's what I thought.
And did students ever bother any of those houses, any of their yards?
No.
No, that's the thing about A&M students.
You never saw all that furrow and the disobedience and things of that kind.
They just didn't exist.
I remember in the 60s when everybody and all of the students all over the country were
were not only harassing, but they were going against the institutions.
And they would have demonstrations, one demonstration after the other.
So some of the students here decided they wanted to demonstrate.
And they got together and they decided they were going to lead those who joined them
right outside to show their strength.
Rudder heard about it, and Rudder went over to, got an opportunity to talk to all of them that's going to demonstrate.
He said, that's fine.
I'm glad you're going to demonstrate.
He said, I'm going to lead you right out of this campus, and you're not coming back.
So I guess you heard that story.
I was here at that time.
You were?
And I remember sometimes he would say, in order to do some of that, you're going to have to walk over this pot-bellied president, and I'm going to stand right here.
He was a great man.
I loved him.
He was splendid.
He was splendid.
I loved him.
What was your core outfit?
Black Eye Company.
Black Eye.
Black Eye.
Oh, I mean, I'll tell you that.
There were some people in there that, they just, they were rowdy, you know.
They would do things and have a lot of tricks.
Describe some of those tricks.
Oh, Lord, I don't know.
Did they do anything ever in the dining hall to somebody else's food?
No, you know what the routine was since you've been here.
Freshmen had to eat under the table, had to eat their kush under the table, all things like that.
But Black Eye Company, for some reason, had a reputation of being a little rowdy and disobedient from time to time, but it was a good company.

right and when y'all it was infantry when y'all fell out to march to y'all march to sabisa for your meals then where did y'all drill in the afternoon no well whenever we were forced to drill because of the of the of the program we drilled on the field on the drill field oh yeah and uh uh did y'all use aggie terminology did you have a fish old lady
Oh, yeah, they had fish-o-laters.
And did you all have the slang in the dining room?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, yeah, they had the slang.
Were there Kush questions?
Kush was dessert.
But did they have Kush questions that a freshman couldn't eat Kush unless he could answer the question?
Oh, they had things like that, yeah.
What was your favorite Sbisa Hall food?
What did you like best?
Oh, I don't know.
I was hungry.
I was so hungry, I ate everything.
It didn't make any difference.
And then when I worked in this greasy spoon restaurant, he gave me 25 cents an hour, and I could eat one meal.
And I ate chili and eggs, because that's the best thing he cooked.
Where was the greasy spoon?
In that area.
Just Northgate?
Yes, I guess you'd call it that.
Do you remember who operated it?
No, I don't remember.
Where did you and your friends go on a Saturday night if you were going to try to have a good time?
Well, I didn't participate too much on the Saturday night or Friday night or whatever it was.
I didn't have the money, and I refused to have people buy me things.
So I didn't participate too much.
Well, where did the other guys, where were their favorite places on a Saturday night?
Oh, they had some places where they got beers or whatever it is, but I never participated in that.
Was there a bootlegger in Brazos County?
I don't know.
There must have been some.
Did any of the students have whiskey in the...
I've seen students with whiskey, yes.
Because that was during Prohibition, so.
Yeah, I've seen them with.
I've seen some that were drunk, had gotten drunk and had little problems.
Did anybody get kicked out of school for drunkenness?
I don't know.
I imagine some were, but I don't know.
As you look back on that first year, what were the best classes?
What were the courses that made an impression on you?
Science.
Science.
About how big was a class then?
How many?
Five, six, maybe eight.
And how well had Beaumont...
When I took my master's degree, there were only two.
How well prepared had Beaumont High made you for college?
How well did you do that first year?
Oh, I did all right in my high school years.
No, but were you...
Were you well prepared for college?
I was well prepared for college because of my determination and wanting to be a geoscientist.
Where did you get your slide rule?
You know, I was looking for my slide rule the other day, and I said, it's got to be here, and I couldn't find it.
I had two.
I had one about this big, and I had one about that big.
And we had some professors would give us a tolerance of 2%, 3%.
And I had one that gave us a tolerance of 5%.
But we learned our mathematics.
We used our slide rule and we carried it.
Everybody carried it with them.
It doesn't make any difference.
God, if we'd had the computers and what we had then, what we got now.
Some of the studies that have taken place, in my opinion, are lackadaisical.
They're not using the brain like they should.
Now, did you bring your slide rule with you, or did you buy it after you bought it?
Oh, I bought it here.
You bought it here.
Oh, yeah.
Do you remember what it cost?
No, no, I don't, but I bought it on time.
Was it new or used?
I know that my little one was used, but the big one that I really needed, I bought new.
And I made arrangements with the people I bought it from, I'd pay them back.
Did you buy it at a place off campus, or was there a bookstore on campus?
It didn't have a bookstore on campus.
I bought it off campus.
When I got my ring, for instance, I wanted a diamond put in there.
Can you see it?
Yes, sir.
Yes, sir.
So I went to the jewelry store and I asked him if I could have a diamond.
He said, yes.
So he brought me some out.
I asked him, how much is that?
He said, $10.
I said, I haven't got that.
I can't pay that.
He brought another one out, $5.
I can't pay that either.
So we kept looking, kept looking.
He finally said, what do you want?
I said, I just want another.
